ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) maps: IP Address → MAC Address. Used inside local networks so devices can communicate.
Example: 192.168.1.1 = aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff
What is ARP Poisoning?
ARP Poisoning (ARP Spoofing / MITM) is when an attacker sends fake ARP replies to victims and gateway.
Goal: Become Man-In-The-Middle, Intercept traffic, Sniff credentials/data, Modify traffic & Cause denial of service
Important ARP Facts: Works only on Local Network, Not routable, No authentication, Trust-based protocol & Easy to abuse

Normal ARP Workflow
ARP Request (Broadcast)
Who has 192.168.1.1?
Tell 192.168.1.12
ARP Reply: 192.168.1.1 is at aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff

Attack Workflow
Attacker sends: 192.168.1.1 is at attacker-MAC
Victim updates ARP cache. Now traffic meant for gateway goes to attacker.

Common Wireshark Filters
Show ARP Traffic: arp
ARP Requests: arp.opcode == 1
ARP Replies: arp.opcode == 2
Possible ARP Scan: arp.dst.hw_mac==00:00:00:00:00:00
Duplicate IP Warning: arp.duplicate-address-detected
Or arp.duplicate-address-frame
Possible ARP Flooding: ((arp) && (arp.opcode == 1))

